Duel to the last blood: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will advise you how to choose
While almost every cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It’s better to just buy the phone.
There are many reasons why you should get a self-employed reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all these musical products do not come out as LPs and from a qualitative point of view for this there is not even an objective reason.
But if your shelves are full of hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls, you probably dream of such a turntable at least.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8 thousand crowns for a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digests the twenty-crown headphones of the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is up to the duration of the batteries.
Some high-quality music players are able to do much more than just read music, which is something mobile phones don’t do by mistake.
There is no other device as universal as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, calling and texting, it can read music and video, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even can navigate.
And if we take smartphones and handhelds into account, you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle that no refrigerator can do the grilling and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone and the sooner the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap cell phones do not count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add us, from time to time, some call, get to work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours at continuous functionality with a charge.
A further problem exists when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory players are able to do without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, except for a few exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Simply fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players create a media library by themselves, sorted by performer name, album name, genre, or user rating.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, focus on the battery resistance, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, ease of use.
If you need music especially as a background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you just need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This can be done, of course, on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about which formats your phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music you get will be in this format.
In addition to this format, which belongs to the most popular ones, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by the company Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument to buy a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is poor and is usually limited only to hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not really low.
But it is generally assumed that this mode of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones with them.
Anyone who wants to listen to something rummage in their pocket while the MP3 player remains forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, if you always carry behind the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an input for the common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped mobile phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
On the other hand, the advantage of readers is, in addition to others, the easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) anyone can really handle them.
The minimum of the functions, the similarity of the handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally crashing the start-up of the mobile internet and consequently a giant bill for data transmission.
Which device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, fall within the 2 000 crowns.
But be careful
The base models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you are part of the most demanding listeners preferably take specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service thus approaches the same MP3 player.
In this area has made more way Sony Ericsson, which mobile phones of the Walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands ensure you the same service and the same price category up to 4,000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery resistance (commonly 15 hours, in principle up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that forces the traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive ones in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> confirmed this, pointing out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regularization of roaming charges perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that would really want to start the clash.
Maybe it sounds absurd, here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
Mobile phone operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, often emphasizes that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer has many possibilities. (After all perhaps it would be difficult now to find other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar rumours were resonating in Britain.
It has been shown, however, that there is a place for such operators and that they can be truly successful.
In the end, for the examples, we do not have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to conquer more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, Mobilking is behind the financial group Penta, to which U:fon belongs in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In other words, it needs far fewer customers than a traditional operator to be able to function effectively.
They do not carry, that is, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low prices, which is often in balance with the most restricted service offer.
So for example Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even the bet on a group-target not for nothing.
This operator focuses, so to speak, specifically on men.
“Real men choose Mobilking as the operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can also be affirmed by us, as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, from the point of view of services, it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no chance, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic, Mobilking will not be one.
"There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, the press spokesperson of the financial group Penta, said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz.
So he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thinking.
On the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated on this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already managed to make progress in negotiations with some of them," says group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information suggests that we may need the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
For now, however, around its creation stands an impenetrable wall of silence.
“Right now we don’t believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press section of Telef<0xC3><0xB2>nika O2.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil Press Spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: “For now we have not noticed any commercial project vital and beneficial to both, on which it is possible to continue to build.”
He adds: “It is unlikely that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobil network before the end of the year.
By now we should have had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this especially in the context of the sharing of expenses and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities - with complicit operators
The attitude of the mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the U:fon creation testify that when operators care about a thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to the information publicly accessible from the web pages of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
But right now U:fon serves as the argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has been further enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would put on him and especially on his high claims services."
The attitude of mobile operators, however, is quite surprising the complete lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not just about the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic – unlike in Great Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, in relation to all the problem has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contracts have been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS external relations section, in the answer to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
On the part of the office, which must defend the interests of consumers and, above all, ensure that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: “Overseas where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services.”
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Just like the identical price of petrol for all petrol stations, it is certainly the result of coincidence and the competitive struggle.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecoms regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s analysis of the relevant markets, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different approach - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has – after all, logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we did not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a minimum alert that three mobile operators proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Unloading responsibility to YOU in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS keeps itself out of the whole affair.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of the rights of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the update of the recently approved telecommunications law, despite the fact that, from this, many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
It can be done when no one is looking
Without realizing it, however, the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
Usually these are companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the predetermined people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company appears to the operator as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer you then receive special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar pre-sale.
"If the cases you are talking about arise, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová answered to the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a profit that is not indifferent and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the regular customers of mobile operators "
But this should be a strange minimum to the <0xC3><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another issue for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS opens up.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want it, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable drop in prices for services.
At the same time in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators more or less tried to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries, in these cases, regulatory bodies have intervened to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and he was followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators throw themselves from one case to the next like a hot potato.
In our experience we can not get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator will appear really soon from us, the Czech mobile phone market will get back in motion.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only <0xC3><0x9A>OHS could hardly remain impassive to the rejection (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
