People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists understand that there is a comparable subjective feeling.
I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult for us to convey our feelings toward animals.
On the one hand, the lateral prefrontal cortex is often connected with human awareness, the associated circuits (this is due to its direct participation in short memory and executive and control functions).
In man this large area is much more developed than in other primates and it seems that among other creatures it is completely missing.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness dependent on the prefrontal cortex, including knowledge, who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, we thus admit the foundation on the assumption that man differs even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity should occur in the way of speaking of man: since a large part of life is connected to language, it is often said to be linked to consciousness.
In this case, the animals could be excluded.
Although awareness does not depend on language, it would influence it so that the awareness of the animal, as it is made, surely differs greatly from the circumstances of our consciousness.
This is why it is difficult to discover how consciousness can be seen in other animals.
If it is not possible to measure it as an internal and subjective thing, in analyzing it through one's own experience because of the special hardware, their research will pose us great problems.
Most interpretations refer to the content of conscious experience, but apart from this there is another aspect of consciousness that science would find easier to access.
One could analyze the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their contents, and this is precisely what happens in studies on the short memory of primates, in particular the example of visualization.
