Interestingly this principle also highlights the value of the prefrontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
What then is delineated for feelings?
I impute them to the fact that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in one of its conscious activities of the brain.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the state of mind in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as the reactions of the body) occupies the working memory.
Seen in this way, the feelings are closely related to the regions of the cortex, which characterize the primates and in particular the human being.
With the speaking nature subtle nuances of feeling are created, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize situations, to describe them to others.
Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that the feelings result from more primitive activities of the body's regions of sensation of the cortex and the paleocephalus, similar to Jack Pankseep, who however focused more on the paleocephalus.
Since this web has not changed much in the course of human evolution, this could absolutely be part of the extended feelings of the species.
On a purely theoretical level, I cannot contradict it, but I consider it indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to rats and humans as fear is likely to be felt with the senses in both cases: but how could it be, if rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave similarly?
A cockroach in case of danger flees as if he too felt fear?
In my eyes the mere similarity of behavior cannot yet demonstrate any vital similarity.
That is, the neural comparison continues to help: rats and humans have similar paleoencephalons, cockroaches not even a brain.
