The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Look, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates’ position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California studies and the senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School.”
Attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s educational projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that, “African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortfalls in achieving goals, Obama’s education plan specifically supports, among other things, “transient bilingual education” for English learners.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes classroom teaching of languages other than English, takes into account his interest in bridging the learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The students at the school are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the top-level test in the 2008 math state exam.
An equally surprising 93 percent of fourth graders took the art-of-language-English expert level test.
This incredible achievement was achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama’s preferred one.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and exercise, constant assessment of skills, and a “no excuses” attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s obstructive approach to English students is “full immersion.”
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Mrs. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, "We had a fantastic success with a student who just came from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you would not have been able to identify what it was."
"It works," he observed, "for us it works."
Would Obama model a school like Sixth Street Prep to replicate it in other Hispanic-majority schools and with English learners?
The results achieved by the school make the answer to that question very easy, but education policy in his own party (the National Education Associations is a long-time supporter of bilingual education) and his own continued support for bilingual education prevent him from predicting Mr. Obama’s answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the topic trivial when he said that people should stop worrying about “English-only” legislation.
Instead, he said, “you have to make sure that your children are able to speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider the educational models that work rather than despise or trivialize them.
