Ethiopia’s Haile Gebrselassie showed again why many consider him the best marathoner ever, breaking his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to run a 26.2 mile run under 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a victory on the race favorably flat in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie shatters for 27 seconds his previous score of 2:03:26, run last year in Berlin.
At 35, Gebrselassie sets the 26th world record for a career so stunning that it has produced a world championship or world record at every distance from the metric mile to the marathon.
