In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Tucked away in the sprawling theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, just a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the enormous, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all-black town incorporated into the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the town of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, Harlem Renaissance’s most famous writer.
Yet in many ways, the city he described—and which makes tourists stop by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project—remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that "knowing so little of us, she doesn't know what she's missing."
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called in for an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider’s gaze.
“We are very cautious about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power grabs and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the rural black culture of the south - sometimes scorned, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really began with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida’s guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through Florida’s often-forgotten downtown into a backdrop of black history and human drama.
Bass as a bass drum in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Outside the street on the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white trim, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked out for, thinking he could just read and write."
She also mentioned the widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever suits passing rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
“Zora said it like it was,” said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls Hurston immortalizes by quoting men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned to her family after moving to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston came to town, he would usually arrive unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts of dignified dress.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others sneered.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But, she added, swinging on her chair on the back patio overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was most likely baptized, “she never stayed long.”
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave at Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big memorial ceremonies, and no big conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relative idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the front door of the community.
“During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on the side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston petitioned the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race."
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, despite having been positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its young people.
“Black kids were used to being hugged — I remember this — hugging your teacher in the morning, hugging your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
“You didn’t embrace your white teacher because your white teacher — I mean, there’s a cultural divide there,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-assurance and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't figure it out."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway hit the shelves of bookstores, reintroducing it to the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had once again caught the limelight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its project for the street.
“The five lanes of the resurrected highway brought what one would call high speed, a real pride for the city,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city’s image of itself.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historical record in 1998.
A new single-storey bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feel of a back road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It’s 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for Eatonville’s story, for its significance, are often still treated with caution.
A permission requested in advance is required for most of the interviews, so some things — like murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a plump teacher with a penchant for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of city pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, trouble and all, neither better nor worse and proud, creative, hardworking, silly and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s grandson, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, which he said may need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“A lot of people, if they’ve just walked in here, they’re going to think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said after Mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty town.”
Here in New York we all speak fluently about finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and huge TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t notice they were in the eye of the storm.
They would never guess that the glass offices, honeycombed above their heads, the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York City are experiencing every day the worst “bad day in the office” since the 1929 meltdown.
The deliverymen shake metal tea carts across the sidewalks, carrying trays of muffins for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans drag their feet between condos carrying, like human mules, 50 and broken shirts strung from a cane on their shoulders.
Employees are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the food carts on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to take a yellow taxi between 4pm and 7pm on a working day.
It didn’t seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon.
