The employees and clerks who stood in front of me, fearful of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe haven, the bank that is asking Wall Street for more collateral.
Ordinary New Yorkers in recent weeks have become proficient in finance.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank, and its emaciated CEO Dick Fuld in all familiarity, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed janitor, nearly 50 years old in my apartment building, has changed the subject from our normal topic of conversation about Brad and Angelina or the delivery of my groceries.
