"Photographer the master away from the scene to extract the character" G<0xC3><0xBC>nther Bauer, photographer
Neither heels nor ruffles nor dresses from before.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in private, in those moments far from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German G<0xC3><0xBC>nther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, seizing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the program of the Flamenco Photography Month, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day more and more," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be about ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, interpreters or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed “on the street” are “artists capable of conveying passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and of capturing the audience.
To capture the personality of these greats it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are internal.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco."
With a passion for the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and the material, resemble classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not dancing, singing or playing in itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, able to conquer the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the gallery El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a sort of flamenco anthology, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, to know them and to be able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or a short moment.
