Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most it takes a scare, but it doesn’t really matter much.
This is a benign sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the baby does not remember anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nighttime fears, bedwetting (wetting in bed), or sleepwalking, but this is not necessarily the case.
As already mentioned, it can be associated with very high fever stages, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very calm tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (scream, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What you can do, however, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite your baby too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more easily.
Once sleepwalkers appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore he is resting.
Remember that if it appears very distressed and the episodes have a certain frequency, it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child derives from.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), don’t fall into the temptation to interrogate him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thinking.
In addition, you are able to hear what it says but not to see what it is dreaming to say it, so you must pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it could lead.
Never tell your child that you might ask him questions during the night to learn his secrets.
Not even as a joke.
Such a thing causes enormous anguish.
In short, do not worry, it is nothing serious, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
