The meeting - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, it has regained the trust of the public, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such tragedy and public outcry, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent a similar disaster from reoccurring.
While Judge Krever was late in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Corporation) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the following years, we have regained the trust of the public," she explains before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its foundation.
“And we didn’t know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when there are doubts and a serious disease could result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are adopted.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for some years, it has been proven that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This incident showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NAT) that make it possible to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have made it possible to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment when the person has contracted the disease to the one in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them has thus decreased considerably.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
“In other words, this means that you will need to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples every year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion to be found.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
“Needs are increasing as the population ages.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average constitutes only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors.
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they get older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that you can hardly find an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Héma-Québec, which operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is an abundance of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the introduction of our 1,000th cord blood sample into the bank, and we plan to collect more than 1,000 cord blood samples each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of cord blood sampling as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
