The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice-president director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation suit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house with the intention of initiating a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to take a position contrary to its own.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a hefty sum of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly odd weapons, against an army of lawyers financed from the virtually bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these odd-arms fights, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that stifles opposition as well as scare anyone who dares to speak out on the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that it should have presented its view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates are usually held with the exchange of opinions and not with truncheons.
It would therefore have been enough for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have much confidence in public opinion and rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is quite evident?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers only to high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrators have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This public is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in view of what many perceive as a kind of gag (by seeking "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum ordering them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal speech, the lawsuit filed by Barrack Gold constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies en bloc the right to quote authentic sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and argue about uncomfortable topics to the richest companies in the world, under penalty of multiple lawsuits, who will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific standards as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right of reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is to the detriment of the university world, as is the public debate in Canada itself, and it is time for governments to take measures to curb abusive lawsuits.
