The psychology of overbidding: why spend more money?
At auctions buyers are inclined to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have been able to uncover the neuro-economic underpinnings of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study that appeared in the journal Science, men don’t want to be left behind in a race such as eBay’s auction, so they are willing to pay a higher price as well.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lotto, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win some money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the body streaked under the cerebral cortex intensively comes into operation when you lose the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the “self-gratification” mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in the price is explained by avoiding the vehement reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group carried out a financial tracking investigation.
In this survey, three groups bid against one partner under different conditions.
To the control group they reported how much was the real value of the product in question and they made their bet.
To another group in addition to this they promised that in case of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose the money in case of loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
By testing the neurologists’ hypothesis, the members of the group playing “against the loss” were willing to make higher bets than the control or “winning” group.
“These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These in fact until now explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we have come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University’s School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to go to the doctor?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, in Hungary instead among the leading causes of death are mentioned chronic liver diseases.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of these only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the alimentary canal (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to get vaccinated against virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and whites of the eyes, the stools become clear and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most severe variant of the disease, which causes liver tumors and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not know they have the disease because the pathogens subtly destroy the liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease it is worth turning to the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 around the world by patient associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
