According to the result of a recent survey, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have carried out an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were electroshocked, while all of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to fend off much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of research in which in addition to academics also scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part.
The test went exactly like this: an instrument that emits shocks and passes the electroshock was attached to the experimenter’s left hand.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the Ermine by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a sort of religious state among believers, while the painting of Leonardo was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a calming effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time frame received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel “secure,” as if “someone was taking care” of them and “they calmed down and were pervaded by peace.”
Looking at the religious-themed image, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you have to find the right image.
"We have to look for an image towards which they have very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it succeeds in changing our personality,” Wright said.
After the excellent results, only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the tenth birthday, Google can claim to be in people’s pockets as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they’ve spent their vacations, which clinic they attend, and what interests them.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s directors, this is still not enough.
As for the skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not see the substance of web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main purpose is to collect as much personal data as its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google’s founders which was: “Let’s put all the information in the world into one system!”
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
To the question what will happen in five years Schmidt answered: he would like if Google could answer questions such as "what do I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?", but the software does not know how to answer seemingly simple questions because they do not know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their internet searches exactly the searched words are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search launched two years ago, for example, users can store their browsing history, they can relate to what they searched and clicked on, these will then in the long run generate much better tailored results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our preferences declared and recorded previously.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? – ask users concerned about Google’s data monopoly.
In most cases, the netizens’ counter-reactions are provoked by the fear felt for the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not for the sense of guilt, for the fear of punishment, for the desire for freedom or even for the rebellion to power.
However, a fact is confirmed, namely that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times has been the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights sighed with relief in May when the company — in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF — successfully demonstrated the truth in court against the FBI: Even later, you can’t force Google with any point in the constitution to provide any information requested secretly by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government has successfully snatched almost 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the Child Protection Act passed years earlier, but still failed to get individual users’ search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data scold Google because they believe that this affects their intimate sphere and private life by starting to use its services and rise up with the rebellion due to the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of computer enthusiasts, activists and users who have appeared in numerous countries see in them the future generation of large companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the package of programs is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies just one of the keywords repeated more often in recent years, the web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, he can connect them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all these can be inserted in systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, he can also write blogs on which automatically appear his most recent photo galleries stored on Flickr or on Picasa.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning from the common circle of friends, easily learns who spent the night with her perfidious boyfriend or a company can fire an employee because he wrote a sincere opinion on the company summit: one thing is certain, the concept of private life has now completely reconsidered.
Those who live a life online make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that hides behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid the monopoly of Google can do it (starting for example with Scroogle using the Google search system but that at the same time does not voluntarily leave traces).
There are many people who do not register on community pages to not be found, Google's online applications, from word processing to image management and newsgathering, can be replaced with alternative versions not linked to huge server parks and that do not make up our best profile so far existing.
Public opinion is not even waiting in secret for the moment when Google will pull out the claws.
Currently the company with its 156 billion dollars of value is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), the advertising spaces AdWords / AdSense threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, the services introduced in record time instead cause great discomfort not only to Microsoft but also to numerous software development companies.
However, the critical observers next to all this find alarming points: the company summit for example completely rejected the protest of the employees after doubling the rate of the company kindergarten, considered too expensive the repeated catering to the daily pleasure of the employees, all this, however, belittles the fact that in 2006 Google bowed the head of the Chinese government and under their agreement the company will filter out all the Chinese interests.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, one thing is for sure, however, that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will move the world at one point: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines of Google we can create such proportions that the company will soon find itself facing the problems of the American Supreme Court Health, others are afraid.
Then the fact that Google is building a genetic database may offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the story Scroogled by the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached in an alarming way.
