Intelligent machine mimics the flight of the hornet
What could be the best method to develop collision avoidance technologies if not mimicking the obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the stunning project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the hornets provided the initial strategic cue to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic minicar with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of avoiding all collisions.
Flying bees form their own personal oval space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the view of the bee, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
The engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to mirror what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation can not go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the steering direction of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to avoid other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, high-energy density lithium polymer batteries, which means they last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, it is the instantaneousness of the intelligent reaction that is important, not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There is no need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, according to Nissan, can be installed on production vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibility of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to the destination.
