Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $ 700 billion rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The New York Times yesterday gives us a confirmation of this by informing us that the ongoing crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, strong especially in the States of the Center and South.
The soul, in fact, which has become powerfully alive with the vow of which I said at the beginning.
But this is only one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps foreshadows or already reveals: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the United States and in Europe, the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of long-incubating phenomena that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the reactualization, the extraordinary relaunch, of the dual category State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, yes, have close links with foreign countries, but which, first of all, see the balance sheets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, involved to a very large extent.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the question or does not have much to say: the clear evidence is given by the European Union which, as usual, is divided between the different interests and between the different state strategies and fails to decide on any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when it comes to the straits it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources can try to put things right.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal increasingly with those things that are very little immaterial that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still linked in an absolute way to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So those who are sovereign, certainly have several more cards than those who are not, those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, however, which foreshadows a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand for someone who knows how to take matters into their own hands.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, economic species, which have proved so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an insufferance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
In other words, it seems to be making more and more way, in large sectors of the population, the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far in vogue, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall meaning of the term, to have done their time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a ramified but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which is manifested in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and very recent times.
One gets the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say, are increasingly struggling to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape today in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis reinvigorates, increases, potentially agitates.
In the face of all this, to speak of a “rebellion of the masses” on the agenda would be frankly an exaggeration.
Keeping your eyes open is certainly not.
