Students victims of car-rents up to 900 euros for a room
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants’ union, taking a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now taken on a very serious character to the point of excluding entire swathes of young people from the right to study for the very high overall costs that families of origin should bear - explains the head of the studies office of Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand from students has so deformed the market as to trigger a process of generalized increase also for the residents ".
In the majority of cases the offers of rent then contain a series of violations: contracts of free type, unregistered, without limit of fee, sub-rents connected.
For Sunia, extraordinary measures are needed which, through the revision of the tax system, can bring down prices.
Looking at the detail of the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room it goes from a minimum of 650 (Black Bands area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas near the University, they need 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, from 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) are asked about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double.
Values only slightly lower (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
You only save if you move to peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 a single in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar areas.
In Naples for a bed you need 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari for a bed you need 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities prices are lower in absolute terms, but have a greater weight in the city economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of rents to non-EU students is more frequent, as in Perugia, there is finally a further anomaly: the increase of about 25/30% of the fee charged to foreign students compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradise, the cities erase the historic cinemas
Historical movie theaters close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of large multisalts and the consequent death by consumption of monosalts in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear to us ineluctable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
“It is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the road and many emotions, were missing,” observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and that perhaps told the poetry of a provincial hall and the nostalgia for a way of life.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of exhibitors, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the biggest payoff is mainly the cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna stands out with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to show that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
<0xC2><0xAB>The Italian exercise has developed irrationally<0xC2><0xBB>, observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, <0xC2><0xAB>it is useful that new structures are built but we should guarantee the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into the multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of allocation for the fund in favor of the merchants: the previous debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from the ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros per year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about closures, has decided to run for cover with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-screen cinemas both in the historic center and in the suburbs.
Among the rules, there are tax relief measures for operators and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
<0xC2><0xAB>It is an initiative that I like<0xC2><0xBB> observes Giuseppe Tornatore<0xC2><0xBB>and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is certain, however, that in order to counteract the overpowering of multiplexes, traditional theatres must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audiences are more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the billboards blackened by the dust I turn to the other side.
Ties between politics and 'Ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to standardize the choices of the municipality to the interests of the so-called Piromalli".
The charges against the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition in a mafia association, are serious.
