When the energy comes from the waves now the big ones come down in the field
It is an endless field, which occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and is now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have set their eyes, and now they are trying to get their hands on giants like the Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalist demands and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be met by sea-wave power plants.
This amount would be double that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later to bet on marine energy are more and more and among these companies always devoted to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies," a spokesman for a subsidiary of the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is not a small signal, especially considering that in Alaska the United States continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has initiated a plan for new drilling.
In addition to the Chevron there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to take the road of the energy that comes from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate according to observers a rising interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: the Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which makes the buoys move up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
The electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
At the moment there are four such plants under design, awaiting only federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines in the East River in New York.
The movement of the water when the tides turn the turbine blades, creating a rotary motion that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, they tell the Institute for Electricity Research, right now deserves the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
It is precisely on tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others bordering the coasts, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and planned investments of up to 35 million for 2009.
